{
  "url": "https://eldritchhorror.fandom.com/wiki/Combat_Encounter",
  "title": "Combat Encounter",
  "intro": "A Combat Encounter is a type of encounter that occurs when the Investigator begins the Encounter Phase while on the same space as a monster. The investigator must encounter every monster that shares his space, one at a time. If there are both non-Epic Monsters and Epic Monsters on the space, the non-Epic Monster(s) must be encountered before the Epic Monster(s) are encountered. (This rule is not in the base game but is part of the rules insert for every expansion.)",
  "combat_rules": {
    "description": "When encountering a Monster, the investigator flips the Monster token facedown and reads the information on the back of the token, resolving any effects that could affect the combat encounter. He then resolves two tests from top to bottom, in most cases a Will test and then a Strength test, to determine the result of the Combat Encounter.",
    "horror_test": {
      "name": "Will Test (Horror)",
      "description": "The Encounter begins by making a Will test against the monster's Horror rating. If the investigator's result is lower than the monster's Horror, the investigator suffers Sanity loss equal to the difference. If the test result is equal to or greater than the rating, he loses no Sanity. Some monsters have no skill listed for this test at all, in which case no skill test is performed."
    },
    "damage_test": {
      "name": "Strength Test (Damage)",
      "description": "Then, the investigator tests Strength against the monster's Damage rating. If this result is lower than the monster's, the investigator suffers Health loss equal to the difference. If the investigator's result is equal or greater than the rating, he loses no Health. If the monster has no Damage rating, the player still performs this test unless otherwise specified on the back of the Monster's token, but there is no possibility of Health loss."
    },
    "defeating_monsters": {
      "description": "If the investigator passes the Damage test, the Monster loses Health equal to the number of successes rolled during the test. Indicate this by placing Health tokens on the Monster token. The investigator and Monster lose Health simultaneously. When a Monster has lost Health equal to or greater than its toughness, the Monster is defeated and returned to the Monster cup. If the Monster is not defeated, it remains on its space along with any Health tokens on it."
    },
    "multiple_monsters": {
      "description": "If there are multiple Monsters on the investigator's space, the investigator must have one Combat Encounter with each one. After all Monsters on the investigator's space have been encountered, if there are no longer any Monsters on the investigator's space (e.g. if they were all defeated in combat), the investigator may have an additional encounter on his space. If there are still one or more Monsters remaining on the space, that investigator does not get to have an additional encounter, and play continues to the next investigator."
    },
    "alternate_skills": {
      "description": "Some Monsters list other skills to test in place of Will and/or Strength; they are handled just like those 2 tests above."
    }
  },
  "examples": [
    {
      "title": "A: Less Success than the Monster's Damage",
      "description": "The investigator fights against a Ghoul which has 1 Toughness and 2 Damage. The investigator rolls Strength and obtains only 1 success. As a result, the investigator loses 1 Health (2 damage from the Ghoul minus 1 success), and the Ghoul loses 1 Health (from the investigator's 1 success) and is defeated."
    },
    {
      "title": "B: Success Equal to the Monster's Damage",
      "description": "The investigator fights against a Goat Spawn which has 1 Toughness and 2 Damage. The investigator rolls Strength and obtains 2 successes. As a result, the investigator does not lose any Health, while the Goat Spawn loses 2 Health due to the investigator's 2 successes and is defeated."
    }
  ],
  "notes": [
    "As with other kinds of tests, if an Investigator rolls at least one success on a Monster's Will/Strength test, that counts as 'passing' the test.",
    "Monster's special effect example: If it states 'if the investigator fails the Will test, he does not resolve the Strength test', and the Monster's Horror rating is 2 and the investigator rolled 1 success on Will test, the investigator passes this test because he rolled at least one success, but still loses 1 Sanity since we subtract number of successes from Monster's Horror rating. If not defeated, he can now perform the Strength test as usual.",
    "If the Monster's special effect states 'if the investigator loses Sanity from the Will test, he does not resolve the Strength test', investigator will not resolve the Strength test since he lost 1 Sanity.",
    "When an effect refers to 'during Combat Encounters', that means when investigators resolve the skill tests printed on the Monster token.",
    "Handcuffs cannot be used while encountering an enemy such as a Colour Out of Space or a Ghost which do not have a Strength test, but can be used to defeat a Cultist of Nephren-Ka which has a Lore test in place of its Strength test.",
    "If a Monster has another skill icon in place of the Strength test indicator, the test is still considered 'the Strength test during a Combat Encounter' even though the actual skill being tested isn't Strength."
  ],
  "ambush": {
    "description": "An Ambush causes a Monster to attack an investigator at a time other than a typical Combat Encounter. This may occur as a result of a Mythos card, a Reckoning effect, or during the Encounter Phase. When an investigator is ambushed, they immediately draw one random Monster and resolve a Combat Encounter with it."
  },
  "physical_and_magical_resistance": {
    "description": "Physical and Magical Resistance are abilities introduced in the Mountains of Madness expansion. They are properties that certain Monsters may have, as indicated on the Monster's token.",
    "rules": [
      "Improvement tokens are not affected by Physical or Magical Resistance.",
      "Effects that allow the investigator to roll 'additional dice', reroll dice, manipulate dice results or cause any effects other than a direct skill bonus (e.g. cause the Monster to lose Health) may be used regardless of the monster's Physical or Magical Resistance."
    ]
  }
}

{
  "url": "https://eldritchhorror.fandom.com/wiki/Defeated",
  "title": "Defeated",
  "intro": "An investigator is defeated when he loses all Health, Sanity, or both, through any means.",
  "defeated_resolution_steps": {
    "description": "When an investigator has lost all Health or Sanity, he is immediately defeated and resolves the following steps:",
    "steps": [
      {
        "step": 1,
        "name": "Advance Doom",
        "description": "Immediately advance Doom by 1."
      },
      {
        "step": 2,
        "name": "Relocation",
        "description": "Move the Investigator token to the nearest City space, or if the investigator is already on a city, leave them where they are. Lay the token on its side and place a Health token on it if the player has lost all Health, or a Sanity token if the player has lost all Sanity. If the player lost all Health and Sanity at the same time, the player may choose which token he wishes to place on the card."
      },
      {
        "step": 3,
        "name": "Collect Possessions",
        "description": "The investigator discard all Conditions, Health and Sanity tokens, Improvement and Impairment tokens, and Focus tokens, then places his possessions on his Investigator sheet. Keep the sheet faceup and place it in a common area, out of the way."
      },
      {
        "step": 4,
        "name": "Pass Lead Investigator",
        "description": "If the defeated investigator has the Lead Investigator token, he must pass it to an investigator of his choice. If all investigators are defeated or are Lost in Time and Space, the Lead Investigator token cannot be passed. The player who had it last keeps it. If an effect refers to the Lead Investigator during that time, the effect will be resolved only if able. For example, the Lead Investigator player could still make a decision, but cannot gain a possession or a Condition because there is currently no investigator to do so."
      }
    ]
  },
  "other_rules": {
    "description": "Additional rules for defeated investigators:",
    "rules": [
      "If an investigator is defeated during an encounter or action, he immediately stops resolving that encounter or action.",
      "The player chooses a new investigator at the end of the Mythos Phase. A player may not choose an investigator that has been previously defeated during the same game.",
      "If the player cannot choose a new investigator because there are none available, he is eliminated.",
      "If the newly chosen investigator requires a starting item that is already in play, he will not get that item.",
      "If an investigator is defeated after the Ancient One awakens, that player is eliminated; this is checking if the Ancient One has awoken at the time the investigator is defeated, not at the end of the Mythos Phase.",
      "If an investigator or multiple investigators are defeated from a single effect and the Doom advancement from their defeat causes the Ancient One to awaken, all of those players will be allowed to select new investigators at the end of that Mythos Phase.",
      "If a single effect causes more than 1 investigator to resolve a Combat Encounter and they are defeated in combat, that doesn't count as defeated by a single effect but rather by their respective Combat Encounter effect. Since the Combat Encounters are resolved one at a time, each investigator up to and including the one whose defeat causes the Ancient One to awaken will not be eliminated. But each investigator defeated after that point will be eliminated.",
      "During the Encounter Phase, an investigator on a space containing a defeated investigator token may encounter it by resolving the Defeated Investigator Encounter on the back of the Investigator sheet in order to gain that investigator's possessions or other benefits, most probably retreating Doom.",
      "The investigator resolves the Crippled effect on the back of the defeated investigator's sheet if the defeated investigator's token has a Health token on it, or the Insane effect if it has a Sanity token on it. After this is completed, remove the investigator token from the board.",
      "When an investigator gains a defeated investigator's possessions, he is considered 'gaining' them. Any effect that triggers when investigators gain possessions (e.g 'When an investigator gains an artifact') will trigger in this case.",
      "If the space a defeated Investigator token is on is devastated, remove the Investigator token from the board."
    ]
  },
  "defeated_investigator_encounters": {
    "description": "If an investigator is on the same space as a defeated investigator, he may do an encounter with that defeated investigator. The investigator follows whichever checks are written on the back of the investigator's sheet, and removes the investigator token from play after this is completed.",
    "mechanics": [
      "In general, encounters with defeated investigators will grant the player the defeated investigators' possessions and will typically retreat Doom if a successful skill check is passed.",
      "When an investigator gains a defeated investigator's possessions, he is gaining them. Effects that trigger on gaining items like Voice of Azathoth would trigger in this case.",
      "The Defeated Encounters are located on the back of each investigator's sheet."
    ]
  }

}

{
  "url": "https://eldritchhorror.fandom.com/wiki/Expedition_Encounters",
  "title": "Expedition Encounters",
  "intro": "The Expedition Encounter is a type of encounter that the player can undertake in Eldritch Horror. The location is determined by the postcard image on the back of the top-most Expedition Encounter card, and the Active Expedition token is placed on that space. That space is the \"Active Expedition space.\" As an encounter, an investigator on the Active Expedition space may draw and resolve an Expedition Encounter. Expedition Encounters are complex encounters, meaning they have three parts: the investigator resolves the top part first, which will typically require them to make a skill test, then they resolve the middle part if they passed the test or the bottom part if they fail the test. Some Expedition Encounters give the player the choice to resolve the pass or fail effect without making a skill test. The reward for a successful Expedition is usually an Artifact. This can be an effective way to gain the items needed for certain Mysteries, as mysteries that require artifacts often allow the player to gain that specific artifact in its place. Other rewards include advancing the Mystery or retreating Doom. After resolving an Expedition Encounter, the investigator moves the Active Expedition token to the space that matches the newly-revealed top card of the Expedition Encounter deck. Note that the \"Active Expedition space\" refers to the space the Active Expedition token is currently on. An \"Expedition space,\" on the other hand, refers to all spaces with an illustration and name presented as a polaroid photograph. Strange Remnants adds the Mystic Ruins Encounter deck, which is functionally similar to an Expedition Encounter deck. Any bonus the player might have to a Mystic Ruins Encounter will usually state that it also applies to an Expedition.",
  "effects_on_expeditions": {
    "description": "Various game components can interact with Expedition Encounters:",
    "examples": [
      "Some Preludes or Rumors can split or shuffle the Expedition deck (e.g. Litany of Secrets).",
      "A Task or Rumor can require to resolve an Expedition Encounter (e.g. Exploring the Ruins).",
      "An Asset can give some bonus to tests when resolving Expedition Encounters (e.g. Expedition Map).",
      "An investigator's ability may interact with Expedition Encounters (e.g. Monterey Jack).",
      "A Unique Asset can allow to shuffle the Expedition deck (e.g. Jake Williams).",
      "As most Expedition Encounters are located on a Wilderness space, all that affect that space type is effective for Expeditions (e.g. Leo Anderson's ability)."
    ]
  },

